[Student "S"]
{North is to play 3NT. East leads the \DK.

Winners:   \S=1  \H=2  \D=1  \C=4  Total = 8

You only need one more winner. If West has the \SK or the \HQ a simple finesse will give you the trick.

There are two problems though. The first one is that if East gets in he may take too many \D tricks. But the bigger problem is that West cannot possibly have either of those two high cards. You and dummy together hold 28 HCP and East must surely hold the other 12 since he opened the bidding. Neither simple finesse will work so you must try what is called a Backward Finesse.

Hold up the \DA until the third round to confirm that West has only 2. He does. Then play four rounds of \Cs ending in your hand.

Now play the \HJ. If East doesn't cover, you will let it ride for your ninth trick. But East does cover so you must take dummy's \HA. Next play a small \H from dummy and finesse the \H9, hoping West has the \H10. This is the Backward Finesse.

The Backward Finesse if a pretty rare play. It is against the odds so you only try it when you are absolutely certain that a normal finesse is doomed to fail.

Like this time.

By the way. Those of you with great short-term memories might think they have seen this hand before. Well, you ALMOST have. Deal 8 has an almost identical layout but a much simpler theme. Check it out.}
[Play "W"]DK

